        <div class="layout-a2__col-a ac-outer-container">

                <h1 class="home-header-with-drop">Northern Ireland local section&#39;s dedication leads to restoration of grave of Belfast science pioneer Thomas Andrews</h1>

            



<div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="text-image-block hashtaglink">

    
    

        <div class="text-image-block__bd">
            <p><strong>The grave of Northern Irish scientific visionary Thomas Andrews was yesterday rededicated in a special ceremony after weeks of restoration work in a Belfast cemetery.</strong></p>
<p>Members of the Royal Society of Chemistry&rsquo;s <a href="/membership-and-community/connect-with-others/geographically/local-sections/northern-ireland/">Northern Ireland section</a> engaged Grave Concern Ireland to restore the resting place of Queen&rsquo;s University Belfast pioneer Thomas Andrews.</p>
<p>The chemical scientist and physicist died in 1885 at the age of 71 and was buried in Belfast City Cemetery at the end of a life that saw him produce research still relevant today.</p>
<p>Among his most significant findings was the discovery of the &lsquo;critical temperature&rsquo; for the liquefaction of carbon dioxide, which is the basis of cryogenics and low-temperature chemistry and physics. The modern refrigerator was also born out of his research on the liquefaction of gases.</p>
<p>As well as restoring the grave and attending the event, members of the RSC&rsquo;s Northern Ireland section also tracked down two members of the extended Andrews family who live locally.</p>
<p>Robert Andrews is a chemistry teacher at Hazelwood College in Belfast, while Johnny Andrews, a chartered accountant in the city, also hopes news of the celebration will help him to find other descendants of the chemistry great.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The Northern Ireland Local Section was involved in getting the Chemistry Landmark plaque for Thomas Andrews and it is fitting that now they have helped to restore his grave,&rdquo; said Dr Dermot Hanna, the secretary of the RSC Northern Ireland local section.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-image-block__img">
            
        <noscript data-slimmage="true" data-img-class="slimmage hashtaglink" data-img-src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-grave-vertical.jpg?version=c5adc99d&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" data-img-alt="image block"><img class="slimmage hashtaglink" src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-grave-vertical.jpg?version=c5adc99d&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" alt="The restored grave of Thomas Andrews in Belfast City Cemetery" alt="image block"></noscript>

    <div class="image-caption">
        <span class="image-caption__caption">The restored grave of Thomas Andrews in Belfast City Cemetery</span>
        <span class="image-caption__credit">Picture: RSC</span>
    </div>

        </div>
            
</div>
</div><div class="block imageblock ">
        <noscript data-slimmage="true" data-img-class="slimmage hashtaglink" data-img-src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/gill-reid-michael-harriott-kevin-morgan-johnny-andrews-robert-andrews-and-helen-pain.jpg?version=c5ade833&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" data-img-alt="image block"><img class="slimmage hashtaglink" src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/gill-reid-michael-harriott-kevin-morgan-johnny-andrews-robert-andrews-and-helen-pain.jpg?version=c5ade833&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" alt="Gill Reid, Michael Harriott, Kevin Morgan, Johnny Andrews, Robert Andrews and Helen Pain stand beside the restored grave of Thomas Andrews" alt="image block"></noscript>

    <div class="image-caption">
        <span class="image-caption__caption">Gill Reid, Michael Harriott, Kevin Morgan, Johnny Andrews, Robert Andrews and Helen Pain stand beside the restored grave of Thomas Andrews</span>
        <span class="image-caption__credit">Picture: Queen&#39;s University Belfast</span>
    </div>
</div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="content-block hashtaglink">

    
    

<hr>            
</div>
</div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="text-image-block hashtaglink">

    
    

        <div class="text-image-block__bd">
            <p>Andrews, who was born and raised in Belfast, took on a number of key roles around the city in the 1830s. In 1835, he became both the professor of chemistry at the Belfast Academical Institution and the attending physician at the Belfast General Hospital. Three years later, he was named medical officer to the Belfast Union Infirmary.</p>
<p>In 1845, he was then appointed the vice-president of the newly established Queen&rsquo;s University of Belfast, resigning from his teaching position and private practice. He also became the first professor of chemistry at Queen&rsquo;s and served in both roles until 1879.</p>
<p>As well as establishing himself an authority in scientific circles, he also served as a president of the Belfast Natural History and Philosophical Society, was elected to the Royal Irish Academy, and became a member &ndash; and then president &ndash; of the Belfast Literary Society.</p>
<p>His work also saw him elected as a fellow of the Royal Society, five years after he received the organisation&rsquo;s prestigious Royal Medal in 1844.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-image-block__img">
            
        <noscript data-slimmage="true" data-img-class="slimmage hashtaglink" data-img-src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews.jpg?version=c5adfb62&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" data-img-alt="image block"><img class="slimmage hashtaglink" src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews.jpg?version=c5adfb62&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" alt="A portrait of Thomas Andrews" alt="image block"></noscript>

    <div class="image-caption">
        <span class="image-caption__caption">A portrait of Thomas Andrews</span>
        <span class="image-caption__credit">Picture: Queen&#39;s University Belfast</span>
    </div>

        </div>
            
</div>
</div><div class="block imageblock ">
        <noscript data-slimmage="true" data-img-class="slimmage hashtaglink" data-img-src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-grave-with-rsc-wreath.jpg?version=c5adc99d&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" data-img-alt="image block"><img class="slimmage hashtaglink" src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-grave-with-rsc-wreath.jpg?version=c5adc99d&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" alt="A yellow, green and blue wreath with an card with the RSC logo in the middle lies at the base of the grave" alt="image block"></noscript>

    <div class="image-caption">
        <span class="image-caption__caption">A wreath provided by the local section was laid at the base of the grave</span>
        <span class="image-caption__credit">Picture: RSC</span>
    </div>
</div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="content-block hashtaglink">

    
    

<hr>            
</div>
</div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="text-image-block hashtaglink">

    
    

        <div class="text-image-block__bd">
            <p>Andrews has previously been honoured by the RSC, which recognised his contribution to science with a <a href="/membership-and-community/chemical-landmarks-blue-plaque-scheme/">National Chemical Landmark blue plaque</a> at Queen's University Belfast in 2013.</p>
<p>RSC representatives were reacquainted with this the day before the grave rededication when they joined staff from Queen's University's chemistry department and library, who laid on a tour and display of some of its impressive array of Andrews artefacts. These included correspondence with Michael Faraday, early photographs of some of his work and other pieces of history.</p>
<p>The tour and the grave rededication exemplified the impact Andrews had on both Queen's and chemistry history.&nbsp;RSC chief executive Dr Helen Pain gave a short speech paying tribute to Andrews and the hard-working members of the local section who honoured him.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="text-image-block__img">
            
        <noscript data-slimmage="true" data-img-class="slimmage hashtaglink" data-img-src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-blue-plaque.jpg?version=c5ae31ff&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" data-img-alt="image block"><img class="slimmage hashtaglink" src="https://epi-rsc.rsc-cdn.org/globalassets/07-news-events/rsc-news/news-articles/2024/04-april/thomas-andrews-grave/thomas-andrews-blue-plaque.jpg?version=c5ae31ff&amp;width=800&amp;format=jpg&amp;quality=80" alt="The National Chemical Landmark plaque in honour of Thomas Andrews, located at Queen&#39;s University Belfast" alt="image block"></noscript>

    <div class="image-caption">
        <span class="image-caption__caption">The National Chemical Landmark plaque in honour of Thomas Andrews, located at Queen&#39;s University Belfast</span>
        <span class="image-caption__credit">Picture: RSC</span>
    </div>

        </div>
            
</div>
</div><div class="block a2maintextblock ">

<div class="content-block hashtaglink">

    
    

<p>&ldquo;The impact of Thomas Andrews&rsquo; work spans generations and the fact it is still relevant today shows how ahead of his time he was,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;We were proud to recognise his efforts with a National Chemical Landmark plaque in 2013 and we are just as proud today to see his resting place restored to a pristine condition.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The members of the local section have done a tremendous job in transforming the site and we hope more people are reminded of the contributions of Thomas Andrews as a result of their hard work.&rdquo;</p>
<ul>
<li>
<h4>Read more about the grave rededication with <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-68794143">this story from BBC Northern Ireland</a>. BBC Newsline also published a short video about the celebration, <a href="https://twitter.com/bbcnewsline/status/1778865136964420058">which you can watch on X/Twitter</a>.</h4>
</li>
</ul>            
</div>
</div><div class="block imageblock ">
